        Board and Secretary
    


Board, Secretary and Committees Membership
Michael Cole BECON, MECON, FFIN Independent Non-Executive Director, Chairman and member of the Audit, Risk & Compliance Committee and Nomination & Remuneration Committee since 10 April 2007.
Mr Cole has over 37 years of experience in the investment banking and the funds management industry.  He was an Executive Director / Executive Vice President at Bankers Trust Australia Limited for over 10 years.  Mr Cole is Chairman of Ironbark Capital Limited and IMB Limited.  Mr Cole is the Chairman and Director of Challenger Listed Investments Limited.
Anne Loveridge BA (Hons), FCA (Australia), FCA (England and Wales), GAICD
Independent Non-Executive Director, Chair of the Audit, Risk & Compliance Committee since 24 February 2017 and member of the Nomination & Remuneration Committee.
Ms Loveridge is currently a Non-Executive Director for the National Australia Bank (NAB) Group and has over 30 years of experience as a former partner in the Financial Services Assurance practice at PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC), where she worked with a range of clients in banking, property, private equity and wealth management sectors providing advice on financial and regulatory reporting, risk management, controls and compliance frameworks.
Stephen Menzies BECON, LLB, LLM,
Independent Non-Executive Director, member of the Audit, Risk & Compliance Committee and Chair of the Nomination & Remuneration Committee since 19 June 2017.
Mr Menzies is currently a Director of Century Australia Investments Limited and Chairman of the Centre for Quantum Computation & Communication Technology. Mr Menzies retired as a partner at Ashurst law firm last year and until his retirement was consistently ranked as one of Australia's leading corporate lawyers. As Head of China Practice for Ashurst, he oversaw the Shanghai and Beijing offices of that firm. As a senior lawyer, he managed legal work of significant projects in capital markets and mergers including some of the largest transactions in Australia. Previously, Mr Menzies was National Director for Enforcement at the Australian Securities Commission and has a long history in the funds management sector.
Kerr Neilson BCOM, ASIP Managing Director since 12 July 1993.
Mr Neilson was appointed as Managing Director upon incorporation of Platinum Investment Management Limited.  Prior to Platinum, Mr Neilson was an Executive Vice President at Bankers Trust Australia Limited. Previously, he worked in both the UK and South Africa in stockbroking.
Andrew Clifford BCOM (HONS) Director and Chief Investment Officer since 8 May 2013.
Mr Clifford joined Platinum as a co-founding member in 1994 in the capacity of Deputy Chief Investment Officer and is a Director of Platinum Investment Management Limited.   Previously he was a Vice President of Bankers Trust Australia Limited covering Asian equities and managing the BT Select Market Trust - Pacific Basin Fund.  Mr Clifford is co-portfolio manager for the Platinum International Fund.
Elizabeth Norman BA, GRAD DIP FP Director since 8 May 2013.
Ms Norman joined Platinum in February 1994 in the role of Investor Services and Communications Manager.  Previously she worked at Bankers Trust Australia Limited in product development and within the retail funds management team.  Ms Norman's role as Director of Investor Services and Communications reflects the widening of Platinum's client base and the company's greater commitment to supporting retail and institutional clients with dedicated investment specialists.
Andrew Stannard BMGT (HONS), GRAD DIP AF&I, CADirector since 10 August 2015.
Mr Stannard joined Platinum from AllianceBernstein where he held the position of Chief Financial Officer for the Asia-Pacific region. Mr Stannard has 25 years of finance experience with expertise in audit, financial control, operations, funds management, financial services regulation and corporate governance. He is a Chartered Accountant.
Joanne Jefferies BCOMM/LLBCompany Secretary since October 2016.
Ms Jefferies joined Platinum from BNP Paribas Securities Services, where she held the positions of Regional Head of Legal for Asia Pacific and Company Secretary. Ms Jefferies has over 20 years of legal experience with expertise in funds management, financial services regulation and corporate governance. Ms Jefferies holds a Bachelor of Laws and a Bachelor of Commerce degree.
 
 






        Corporate Responsibility and Sustainability
    


Building a Sustainable Business
2014 was a milestone year – Platinum celebrated its 20th anniversary and its funds under management (FUM)1 exceeded A$25 billion.
From a starting-point of a team of four investment professionals and a handful of support staff, Platinum has built a strong brand name and a reputation that is the envy of the financial services industry.  This reputation has been achieved by staying true to Platinum’s key objective – delivering superior returns over time and communicating the intricacies of global investing (and providing investors with steady long-term performance.)
The business of Platinum is to manage clients’ money.  It charges clients a fee for doing so, and these fees are Platinum’s chief source of revenue.  We, at Platinum, have a simple core belief:  if Platinum responsibly and successfully looks after investors’ money, its business should prosper.  A failure to understand and commit to this priority will not result in an enduring wealth management business; marketing, commissions and other devices notwithstanding.

Being a Responsible Money Manager
History of Strong Performance
Our history has been punctuated with recurrent market challenges – the Asian monetary crisis of 1997-98, the tech bubble of 2000-01, and the more recent global financial crisis of 2007-08.  In spite of these challenges, we have seized the many opportunities presented by the market and have over the long-term typically outperformed the benchmark MSCI Index by a significant margin.  As at 31 May 2016, the flagship Platinum International Fund had achieved an average compound annual return of 12.65% since its inception in 1995, compared to 6.28% for the MSCI All Country World Net Index.  Indeed, the majority of our Platinum Trust Funds have performed strongly over the long-term, delivering superior returns to our investors.
Click here for more information on the performance of all publicly available Platinum funds.
Investment Process
How did we achieve these strong returns?  Platinum is well-known for its distinctive stock selection methodology which seeks out a broad range of investments where the market has, for transient reasons, mispriced their business.  To do this, Platinum employs a team of highly skilled specialist analysts, who take a global perspective and apply screening and intensive research to isolate real as opposed to imagined issues.
In applying Platinum’s thematic, contrarian investment method, we build each portfolio from individual stock selections rather than from any pre-determined asset allocation. At times whole sectors or industries may be misunderstood and this can give rise to several investments in that and related areas. We pay no heed to the weightings of any benchmark, such as the MSCI Index.  
Investment risks are actively monitored and managed through appropriate measures such as the use of derivatives and currency hedging (where permitted under the fund’s mandate).
A more detailed description of our investment process can be found here and click here for further information on Platinum’s risk management strategies.
Better Engagement with Investors
In addition to the core principle of striving for superior long-term performance in global equity investments, Platinum’s business has been founded on the following precepts:

No up-front fees;
No exit fees;
No trailing commissions to financial intermediaries or advisers;
No soft dollar benefits paid to or received from financial advisers or advisory firms;
Forward pricing (no “market timing” or “late trading”) of unit trust products;
We support financial advisers with quality presentations from the investment team;
We give biennial investor presentations for those investing directly with us;
We provide clear and engaging quarterly investor reports;
We provide consistent high service standards to clients and advisers.

All of these principles were adopted with the single aim of better servicing our clients, and none of which has altered over the 22 years of Platinum’s growth.
Ethical Conduct
The ethical standards of the financial services industry have been facing increasing scrutiny worldwide since the global financial crisis.  Platinum has always held the highest standards of integrity and honesty and has put in place robust policies aiming to prevent unethical conduct such as fraud, bribery and insider trading.  Given the nature of Platinum’s business, we are particularly mindful of the risks of insider trading and personal dealing.  Platinum has therefore implemented appropriate systems of ongoing monitoring and regular training to ensure compliance by all staff members with our Business Rules of Conduct and Trading Policy.
Ethical Investment
Platinum regards the subject of ethical investing as highly complex and points to the contradictions and conflicts that are an essential element of the capitalist system.  We have no way of individually assessing the beliefs and values of our investors or the companies in which we invest.
Cognisant of the diversity of views on these subjects, Platinum decided at this stage not to adopt any formalised ethical investment policy in selecting, retaining and realising investments.  However, that is not to say that ethical considerations such as environmental responsibility and labour standards do not play a part in our investment process.  Our investment analysts routinely take such factors into consideration when assessing the overall quality and sustainability of an investment prospect. (It has been our experience that when our values of fair play and ethics are upheld by the company under scrutiny, it tends to lead to fewer disappointments as an investment.) 
To adopt a more formal set of ethical investment criteria would require Platinum to develop a template of ethical values that (hopefully) satisfies the majority of unit holders on matters including labour standards, environmental impact, social intercourse, political system, governance behaviour and standards, national institutions and so on.  In our view, it is not possible to create such a template without unduly imposing a set of values on all investors regardless of whether they share these values.
Workplace Diversity and Flexibility
In a service-oriented business like Platinum, our people are our greatest asset.  That is why we focus equally on attracting the best talent and providing an inclusive and supportive work environment for our staff.
Platinum actively promotes a culture of equal opportunity and has the principles of meritocracy, fairness, equality and contribution to commercial success at all levels within the Company.  We value the blend of skills, perspectives, styles and attitudes available to the Company through a diverse workforce and recognise that such diversity has contributed to our business success.  (For example, our investment research team includes not only economists and finance experts, but also scientists and engineers.  You can find more information about our investment team here.)
In this context, workplace diversity includes gender, age, ethnicity, cultural background and more.  To promote workplace diversity, our Board has adopted a Diversity Policy in addition to a Workplace Anti-Discrimination & Anti-Harassment Policy.  The Diversity Policy includes a set of clear objectives as part of our corporate governance practice.  These include:

To provide flexibility to staff members.  In this context, workplace flexibility involves developing people management strategies that accommodate differences in background, perspectives and family responsibilities of staff.
To include in the recruitment process for vacant positions a diversified group (including gender diversity) of candidates.  This further extends to the interview process for vacant positions on Platinum’s Board of Directors.
To provide training opportunities with the aim of bringing through the underlying potential of staff.
Established a diversity committee comprising representatives from each business area.  The diversity committee will meet periodically and will monitor progress on Board-recommended diversity strategies and make recommendations to the Board for further diversity opportunities.

The following statistics (current as of 11 May 2016) demonstrate Platinum’s ongoing endeavours to promote diversity and flexible work arrangements.  This has allowed Platinum to exceed the country’s average in many aspects, for example, the representation of women on the board and in senior executive positions, women employed on a part-time basis, and the percentage of workforce made up of people born outside Australia.
 




